  "prompt": "I changed the headers and meta tags on my site and my developer said it messed up the design. Can this be true?",
  "response": "Headers and meta tags typically do not directly affect the design or layout of a website. They are mainly used for:\n\n1. Meta tags:\n- SEO information\n- Page description\n- Character encoding\n- Viewport settings\n- Social media sharing details\n\n2. HTTP headers:\n- Caching instructions\n- Content type\n- Security settings\n\nIf your developer claims the design was affected, they might be referring to:\n\n1. Viewport meta tag changes\n- Could impact responsive design\n- Affects how site scales on different devices\n\n2. Possible indirect interactions with:\n- CSS frameworks\n- JavaScript rendering\n- Specific site configurations\n\nRecommendations:\n- Ask developer for specific details\n- Request screenshot of changes\n- Review exactly which tags were modified\n- Check if any critical meta tags were unintentionally altered\n\nMost likely, the design issues are coincidental or related to something else. Headers and meta tags rarely cause direct design disruptions.\n\nWould you like me to help you review the specific changes you made?",
